t\t\t\t\t<string>{{105.5, 286}, {152.5, 22.998817901802376}}</string>\ndocs/resources/trigeminal.graffle:3302:\t\t\t\t\t<string>{{51.000002092243903, 83.999420166015625}, {314, 58}}</string>\ndocs/resources/trigeminal.graffle:3740:\t\t\t\t\t<string>{{450.79939135690108, 25.500590790704919}, {53.253826141357422, 22}}</string>\ndocs/resources/trigeminal.graffle:3821:\t\t\t\t\t<string>{{512.99992145395527, 286.24282736446708}, {80.000160217285156, 22}}</string>\ndocs/resources/trigeminal.graffle:4099:\t\t\t\t\t<string>{{339.00000052306098, 286}, {173.5, 22.998817443847656}}</string>\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:6610:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"FB:ma\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:dsd\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMCID:PMC2613570\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:10102814\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:16923606\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:17986482\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19960544\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesenchymal_stem_cell\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"http://www.copewithcytokines.de/cope.cgi?key=mesenchymal%20stem%20cells\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000134 \"A connective tissue cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses. In humans, this cell type is CD73-positive, CD90-positive, CD105-positive, CD45-negative, CD34-negative, and MHCII-negative. They may further differentiate into osteoblasts, adipocytes, myocytes, neurons, or chondroblasts in vitro. Originally described as residing in the bone marrow, this cell type is now known to reside in many, if not all, adult organs.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:8529:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"MESH:D012629\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19944183\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000317 \"An epithelial cell that is part of a sebaceous gland. This cell produces and secretes sebum, an oily, lipid-rich substance, through holocrine secretion where the entire cell ruptures to release its contents.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:10003:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:add\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:dsd\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19923473\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:9354811\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000484 \"Mast cell subtype whose granules contain both the serine proteases tryptase and chymase. These cells are primarily found in connective tissue, such as the peritoneal cavity, skin, and intestinal submucosa. Their development is T-cell independent.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:10017:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:add\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:dsd\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19923473\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:9354811\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000485 \"Mast cell subtype that contains only the serine protease trypase in its granules. These cells are primarily found in mucosal tissue, such as intestinal mucosa and alveoli. They depend upon T-cells for development of phenotype.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:13343:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:add\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:amm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:dsd\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"ISBN:0721601464\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"MESH:D001491\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMCID:PMC2626675\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:11927641\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19741522\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:21236338\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:9933081\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000767 \"Any of the immature or mature forms of a granular leukocyte that in its mature form has an irregularly shaped, pale-staining nucleus that is partially constricted into two lobes, and with cytoplasm that contains coarse, bluish-black granules of variable size. Basophils contain vasoactive amines such as histamine and serotonin, which are released on appropriate stimulation. A basophil is CD123-positive, CD193-positive, CD203c-positive, and FceRIa-positive.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:15201:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:ana\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GO_REF:0000031\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19906191\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000884 \"A tissue-resident macrophage found in the mucosa associated lymphoid tissue.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:15209:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:ana\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GO_REF:0000031\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19906191\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000885 \"A mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue macrophage found in the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues of the gut.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:15727:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:add\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:pam\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GO_REF:0000031\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:22343568\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:9914231\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000917 \"A CD8-positive, alpha-beta positive T cell that has the phenotype T-bet-positive, eomesodermin-positive, CXCR3-positive, CCR6-negative, and is capable of producing interferon-gamma.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:15753:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:add\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:pam\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GO_REF:0000031\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:9914231\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000918 \"A CD8-positive, alpha-beta positive T cell expressing GATA-3 and secreting IL-4.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:16146:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:add\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:pam\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GO_REF:0000031\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19941119\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0000942 \"A plasmacytoid dendritic cell developing in the thymus with phenotype CD11c-negative or low, CD45RA-positive, CD11b-negative, and CD123-positive.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:19188:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"FMA:0412046911\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19939742\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0002068 \"Specialized cardiac myocyte that is subendocardially interspersed with the regular cardiac muscle cell. They are uninucleate cylindrical cells, associated end-to-end in long rows, continue from the node to the atrioventricular bundle; relatively short compared to ordinary myocytes but are nearly twice their diameter.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:21142:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1016/j.biocel.2007.10.034\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1111/aos.14600\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1155/2021/9951032\") terms:description obo:CL_0002223 \"The anterior lens cells, also known as lens epithelial cells, are an integral part of the eye's structure and play a critical role in the organ's physiological functioning. They are situated in the anterior portion of the lens, precisely in the lens capsule, and stretch over the lens' frontal surface.\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:22723:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19949422\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"http:www.immgen.org/index_content.html\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0002345 \"An immature natural killer cell that is NK1.1-positive, DX5-positive, Ly49-positive, CD27-low and CD11b-low. This cell type is found in high numbers in the liver.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:22753:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19949422\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0002347 \"A mature natural killer cell that is CD27-high and CD11b-high. This cell type is capable of interferon-gamma secretion.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:25839:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1177/0036850419850431\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1203/00006450-199811000-00001\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.3791/56639\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532927/\") terms:description obo:CL_0002601 \"Uterine smooth muscle cells are specialized cells that make up the majority of the uterus and in particular, the myometrium. The myometrium is a thick, involuntary muscle layer, principally consisting of verticillate cell bundles that sculpt the helical architecture of the uterus. This dense muscular tissue, packed with uterine smooth muscle cells, is responsible for the significant contractile force witnessed during the physical processes of labor and childbirth.\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:26055:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"GOC:tfm\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:20807818\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:9020076\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Endothelial_progenitor_cell&oldid=1069930016\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0002619 \"An adult angioblastic cell released from the bone marrow, or from the kidney in some teleost species, capable of blood circulation and participation in angiogenesis by differentiating into blood vessel endothelial cells.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:30258:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Endothelial_progenitor_cell&oldid=1069930016#Colony_forming_unit_–_Hill\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0009085 \"An adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. They may form discrete colonies.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:30292:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Endothelial_progenitor_cell&oldid=1069930016#Circulating_angiogenic_cell\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_0009088 \"An adult endothelial progenitor cell characterised in vivo by homing to ischemic sites and paracrine support of angiogenesis. These cells do not form colonies.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:37981:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.11165918\") rdfs:comment obo:CL_4023036 \"The marker set GPR149, CA8 can identify the Human cell type chandelier pvalb GABAergic cortical interneuron in the Brain with a confidence of 0.799748111 (NS-Forest FBeta value).\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:38116:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.11165918\") rdfs:comment obo:CL_4023046 \"The marker set CCN2, ROS1 can identify the Human cell type L6b glutamatergic neuron of the primary motor cortex in the Brain with a confidence of 0.819940964 (NS-Forest FBeta value).\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:38490:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Martinotti_cell&oldid=9947732\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4023076 \"An interneuron that has Martinotti morphology. These interneurons are scattered throughout various layers of the cerebral cortex, sending their axons up to the cortical layer I where they form axonal arborization.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:38847:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Spiral_ganglion&oldid=994446209\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4023115 \"A spiral ganglion neuron that innervates inner hair cells. Type 1 spiral ganglion neurons are myelinated and bipolar.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:38850:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Spiral_ganglion&oldid=994446209\") rdfs:comment obo:CL_4023115 \"Type 1 spiral ganglion neurons comprise the vast majority of spiral ganglion cells.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:38860:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Spiral_ganglion&oldid=994446209\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4023116 \"A spiral ganglion neuron that innervates outer hair cells. Type 1 spiral ganglion neurons are unmyelinated and unipolar.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:38863:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Spiral_ganglion&oldid=994446209\") rdfs:comment obo:CL_4023116 \"Outer hair cells form reciprocal synapses onto type 2 spiral ganglion cells, suggesting that the type 2 cells have both afferent and efferent roles.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:39109:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:22190641\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"WikipediaVersioned:Trigeminal_nerve&oldid=1099897926\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4023169 \"A neuron that is responsible for sensation in the face or motor functions such as biting and chewing. Trigeminal neurons extend a single axon shaft along the lateral white matter of the hindbrain and spinal cord. The highly branched axons innervate the integument of the head.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:39138:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1002/(SICI)1097-0029(19980415)41:2<98::AID-JEMT2>3.0.CO;2-M\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1111/joa.13709\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.3389/fncel.2015.00480\") terms:description obo:CL_4023181 \"Hypendymal cells are secretory cells located between the ependymal layer and the posterior commissure, forming the hypendmal layer of the subcommissural organ (SCO), a highly conserved gland that is part of the circumventricular system within the brain. \nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:40138:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.11165918\") rdfs:comment obo:CL_4030067 \"The marker set NPSR1-AS1, TLL1 can identify the Human cell type L5/6 near-projecting glutamatergic neuron in the Brain with a confidence of 0.899288218 (NS-Forest FBeta value).\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:40185:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:29904965\") oboInOwl:hasExactSynonym obo:CL_4032001 \"rln GABAergic cortical interneuron\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:40223:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19996346\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:5487122\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4033003 \"A(n) myoepithelial cell that is part of a(n) bronchus submucosal gland.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:40475:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19965983\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4033022 \"A mucus secreting cell of a submucosal gland of the bronchus.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:42255:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:19906678\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:21865647\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:26964064\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:28066889\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:33731961\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4047042 \"An enteric glial cell located within the myenteric ganglia of the gastrointestinal tract. This cell has a small somata and has very short, irregularly branched processes that surround neuron cell bodies, giving it a protoplasmic-like appearance. It plays crucial roles in modulating myenteric neuron activity, regulating oxidative stress, and influencing neuroinflammation and neurogenesis.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-cl.owl:42294:AnnotationAssertion(Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"DOI:10.1016/j.celrep.2023.112194\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:29927320\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:33731961\") Annotation(oboInOwl:hasDbXref \"PMID:35111752\") obo:IAO_0000115 obo:CL_4047047 \"An enteric glial cell located within the ganglia of the enteric nervous system. This cell is characterized by it’s small somata and short, irregularly branched processes that surround neuronal cell bodies in the myenteric and submucosal ganglia. This cell plays important roles in modulating neuronal activity and neurogenesis in the gastrointestinal tract.\")\nsrc/ontology/imports/local-xao.owl:21:Annotation(oboInOwl:NamespaceIdRule \"* XAO:$sequence(7,6000,9999999)$\")\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:4164:property_value: homology_notes \"The homologization of cranial bones of actinopterygians with those of sarcopterygians based on the bone names established in human anatomy is favored in order to permit the building of phylogenetic relationship schemes beyond the taxonomic boundaries of osteichthyans (including tetrapods). (...) In actinopterygians, the terms parietal and postparietal bones have to replace the commonly used terms 'frontal' and 'parietal' bones for the two paired bones on the skull roof.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001326\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"ISBN:978-3899370805 Arratia G, Schultze HP, Wilson MVH, Mesozoic Fishes 4 - Homology and Phylogeny (2008) p.23-48\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:5676:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/399916008\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:7805:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279979000\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:13580:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279929003\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:14534:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279965008\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:15114:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279995000\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:18306:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/269922006\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:19887:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279914000\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:28666:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/29972009\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:29187:property_value: homology_notes \"The infraorbital bone 1 of actinopterygians is homologous with the lacrimal bone (...).[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001149\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"ISBN:978-3899370805 Arratia G, Schultze HP, Wilson MVH, Mesozoic Fishes 4 - Homology and Phylogeny (2008) p.23-48\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:29309:property_value: homology_notes \"(...) and the infraorbital bone 3 of advanced actinopterygians (is homologous) with the jugal bone of sarcopterygians.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001638\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"ISBN:978-3899370805 Arratia G, Schultze HP, Wilson MVH, Mesozoic Fishes 4 - Homology and Phylogeny (2008) p.23-48\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:29862:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279927001\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:29922:property_value: homology_notes \"These (the epibranchial placodes) are focal thickenings of the embryonic ectoderm that form immediately dorsal and caudal of the clefts between the pharyngeal arches in all vertebrates, and they produce the neuroblasts which migrate and condense to form the distal cranial ganglia: the geniculate, petrosal and nodose ganglia. (...) The one substantial difference between the vertebrate pharyngeal arches and those of the protochordates is the presence of the epibranchial placodes but the evolution of these structures was undoubtedly driven by the endoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000707\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:29951:property_value: homology_notes \"These (the epibranchial placodes) are focal thickenings of the embryonic ectoderm that form immediately dorsal and caudal of the clefts between the pharyngeal arches in all vertebrates, and they produce the neuroblasts which migrate and condense to form the distal cranial ganglia: the geniculate, petrosal and nodose ganglia. (...) The one substantial difference between the vertebrate pharyngeal arches and those of the protochordates is the presence of the epibranchial placodes but the evolution of these structures was undoubtedly driven by the endoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000702\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:30227:property_value: homology_notes \"Subsequent vertebrate evolution has also involved major alterations to the pharynx; perhaps the most notable occurred with the evolution of the gnathostomes. This involved substantial modifications to the most anterior pharyngeal segments, with the jaw forming from the first, anterior, pharyngeal segment, while the second formed its supporting apparatus, the hyoid.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000454\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:30260:property_value: homology_notes \"Subsequent vertebrate evolution has also involved major alterations to the pharynx; perhaps the most notable occurred with the evolution of the gnathostomes. This involved substantial modifications to the most anterior pharyngeal segments, with the jaw forming from the first, anterior, pharyngeal segment, while the second formed its supporting apparatus, the hyoid.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000453\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:30869:property_value: homology_notes \"Experients in amphibia have shown that an intrinsic feature of the pharyngeal endoderm is its ability to generate taste buds and this capacity must have been acquired by the endoderm at the origin of the vertebrates.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000130\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:36450:property_value: homology_notes \"The epithalamus has been historically conceived as a distinct neuroanatomical moiety within the diencephalon of all vertebrates. (...) The evolutionary origins of epithalamic structures are uncertain but asymmetry in this region is likely to have existed at the origin of the vertebrate, perhaps even the chordate, lineage.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000178\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910063.x Concha ML and Wilson SW, Asymmetry in the epithalamus of vertebrates. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:40812:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/319910005\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:43352:property_value: homology_notes \"The presence of a gallbladder appears to be a primitive trait. It is found in most fish and all adult reptiles and amphibians and has been well conserved in mammals, for the most part.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000221\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1002/(SICI)1097-0029(19970915)38:6<571::AID-JEMT3>3.0.CO;2-I Oldham-Ott CK, Gilloteaux J, Comparative morphology of the gallbladder and biliary tract in vertebrates: Variation in structure, homology in function and gallstones. Microscopy research and technique (1997)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:46948:property_value: homology_notes \"The homologization of cranial bones of actinopterygians with those of sarcopterygians based on the bone names established in human anatomy is favored in order to permit the building of phylogenetic relationship schemes beyond the taxonomic boundaries of osteichthyans (including tetrapods). (...) In actinopterygians, the terms parietal and postparietal bones have to replace the commonly used terms 'frontal' and 'parietal' bones for the two paired bones on the skull roof.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001327\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"ISBN:978-3899370805 Arratia G, Schultze HP, Wilson MVH, Mesozoic Fishes 4 - Homology and Phylogeny (2008) p.23-48\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:50155:property_value: homology_notes \"(...) the ability of ectoderm to produce neuronal cells is a general metazoan feature.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000150\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:69227:property_value: homology_notes \"These (the epibranchial placodes) are focal thickenings of the embryonic ectoderm that form immediately dorsal and caudal of the clefts between the pharyngeal arches in all vertebrates, and they produce the neuroblasts which migrate and condense to form the distal cranial ganglia: the geniculate, petrosal and nodose ganglia. (...) The one substantial difference between the vertebrate pharyngeal arches and those of the protochordates is the presence of the epibranchial placodes but the evolution of these structures was undoubtedly driven by the endoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000117\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A, The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:74055:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/189936008\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:74882:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/359923002\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:87830:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/299705008\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:89201:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/299711006\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:89224:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/299710007\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:89246:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/299708005\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:90678:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279999006\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:90691:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279998003\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:94246:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/29926005\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:98402:property_value: homology_notes \"The homologization of cranial bones of actinopterygians with those of sarcopterygians based on the bone names established in human anatomy is favored in order to permit the building of phylogenetic relationship schemes beyond the taxonomic boundaries of osteichthyans (including tetrapods). (...) In actinopterygians, the terms parietal and postparietal bones have to replace the commonly used terms 'frontal' and 'parietal' bones for the two paired bones on the skull roof.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001327\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"ISBN:978-3899370805 Arratia G, Schultze HP, Wilson MVH, Mesozoic Fishes 4 - Homology and Phylogeny (2008) p.23-48\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:99020:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/279973004\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:99939:xref: http://www.snomedbrowser.com/Codes/Details/299626000\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:105664:property_value: homology_notes \"These (the epibranchial placodes) are focal thickenings of the embryonic ectoderm that form immediately dorsal and caudal of the clefts between the pharyngeal arches in all vertebrates, and they produce the neuroblasts which migrate and condense to form the distal cranial ganglia: the geniculate, petrosal and nodose ganglia. (...) The one substantial difference between the vertebrate pharyngeal arches and those of the protochordates is the presence of the epibranchial placodes but the evolution of these structures was undoubtedly driven by the endoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000685\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:107199:consider: SCTID:429921001\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:110161:property_value: homology_notes \"In all vertebrates, the pharyngeal apparatus develops from a series of bulges found on the lateral surface of the head, the pharyngeal arches, which consist of a number of different embryonic cell types. Each arch has an external covering of ectoderm and inner covering of endoderm, and between these a mesenchymal filling of neural crest with a central core of mesoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001062\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:110178:property_value: homology_notes \"In all vertebrates, the pharyngeal apparatus develops from a series of bulges found on the lateral surface of the head, the pharyngeal arches, which consist of a number of different embryonic cell types. Each arch has an external covering of ectoderm and inner covering of endoderm, and between these a mesenchymal filling of neural crest with a central core of mesoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0000946\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.2001.19910133.x Graham A. The development and evolution of the pharyngeal arches. J Anat (2001)\"}\nsrc/ontology/taxmods/uberon-taxmod-amniote.obo:110195:property_value: homology_notes \"In all vertebrates, the pharyngeal apparatus develops from a series of bulges found on the lateral surface of the head, the pharyngeal arches, which consist of a number of different embryonic cell types. Each arch has an external covering of ectoderm and inner covering of endoderm, and between these a mesenchymal filling of neural crest with a central core of mesoderm.[well established][VHOG]\" xsd:string {date_retrieved=\"2012-09-17\", external_class=\"VHOG:0001095\", ontology=\"VHOG\", source=\"http://bgee.unil.ch/\", source=\"DOI:10.1046/j.1469-7580.20